{"id":"2301.00932","submitter":"Stephan Dominique Andres","authors":"Stephan Dominique Andres, Wai Lam Fong","title":"Line game-perfect graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The $[X,Y]$-edge colouring game is played with a set of $k$ colours on a\ngraph $G$ with initially uncoloured edges by two players, Alice (A) and Bob\n(B). The players move alternately. Player $X\\in\\{A,B\\}$ has the first move.\n$Y\\in\\{A,B,-\\}$. If $Y\\in\\{A,B\\}$, then only player $Y$ may skip any move,\notherwise skipping is not allowed for any player. A move consists in colouring\nan uncoloured edge with one of the $k$ colours such that adjacent edges have\ndistinct colours. When no more moves are possible, the game ends. If every edge\nis coloured in the end, Alice wins; otherwise, Bob wins.\n  The $[X,Y]$-game chromatic index $\\chi_{[X,Y]}'(G)$ is the smallest\nnonnegative integer $k$ such that Alice has a winning strategy for the\n$[X,Y]$-edge colouring game played on $G$ with $k$ colours. The graph $G$ is\ncalled line $[X,Y]$-perfect if, for any edge-induced subgraph $H$ of $G$,\n\\[\\chi_{[X,Y]}'(H)=\\omega(L(H)),\\] where $\\omega(L(H))$ denotes the clique\nnumber of the line graph of $H$.\n  For each of the six possibilities $(X,Y)\\in\\{A,B\\}\\times\\{A,B,-\\}$, we\ncharacterise line $[X,Y]$-perfect graphs by forbidden (edge-induced) subgraphs\nand by explicit structural descriptions, respectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Jan 2023 02:35:07 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 16 Feb 2023 13:03:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-17"}
