{"id":"2301.00937","submitter":"Jing Wang","authors":"Jing Wang, Dong Yang, Se-Heon Oh, Lister Staveley-Smith, Jie Wang, Q.\n  Daniel Wang, Kelley M. Hess, Luis C. Ho, Ligang Hou, Yingjie Jing, Peter\n  Kamphuis, Fujia Li, Xuchen Lin, Ziming Liu, Li Shao, Shun Wang, Ming Zhu","title":"FEASTS: IGM cooling triggered by tidal interactions through the diffuse\n  HI phase around NGC 4631","comments":"35 pages, 24 figures. Accepted for publication at ApJ. FEASTS site:\n  http://kavli.pku.edu.cn/~jwang/FEASTS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.3847/1538-4357/acafe8","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.GA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We use the single-dish radio telescope FAST to map the HI in the tidally\ninteracting NGC 4631 group with a resolution of 3.24$'$ (7 kpc), reaching a\n5-$\\sigma$ column density limit of $10^{17.9}$ cm$^{-2}$ assuming a line width\nof 20 km s$^{-1}$. Taking the existing interferometric HI image from the\nHALOGAS project of WSRT as reference, we are able to identify and characterize\na significant excess of large-scale, low-density, and diffuse HI in the group.\nThis diffuse HI extends for more than 120 kpc across, and accounts for more\nthan one fourth of the total HI detected by FAST in and around the galaxy NGC\n4631. In the region of the tidal tails, the diffuse HI has a typical column\ndensity above $10^{19.5}$ cm$^{-2}$, and is highly turbulent with a velocity\ndispersion around 50 km s$^{-1}$. It increases in column density with the dense\nHI, and tends to be associated with the kinematically ``hotter'' part of the\ndense HI. Through simple modeling, we find that the majority of the diffuse HI\nin the tail region is likely to induce cooling out of the hot IGM instead of\nevaporating or being radiatively ionized. Given these relations of gas in\ndifferent phases, the diffuse HI may represent a condensing phase of the IGM.\nActive tidal interactions on-going and in the past may have produced the\nwide-spreading HI distribution, and triggered the gas accretion to NGC 4631\nthrough the phase of the diffuse HI.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Jan 2023 03:19:31 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-22"}
